COWPOX, RODENTS, HUMAN - GERMANY, FRANCE ex CZECH REPUBLIC
**********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Fri 20 Feb 2009
Source: Konsurmo [in German, trans. submitter SZ, edited]
<http://www.konsumo.de/news/2900-Haustier-Ratte-Kuhpocken-NRW-Bayern-Infektion-krank-Ratten-Virus>


Pet rats transmit cowpox to humans
----------------------------------
Keepers of pet rats are at risk of infection with cowpox virus in
parts of Germany --North Rhine-Westphalia (NRW) and Bavaria -- and in
northern France infections of humans with cowpox virus have recently
been confirmed. The virus is thought to be transmitted through direct
contact with rats, kept as pets. Infected humans show flu-like
symptoms and rash. If an infection in humans occurs the typical signs
are flu-like symptoms such as fever, fatigue, and itchy rashes and
blisters of the skin. The rashes heal after several weeks, leaving
crusts and scars. Often the virus causes conjunctivitis. Especially
when these signs of an infection are seen patients are advised to see
their doctor, the National Office for Nature, Environment and
Consumer Protection, North Rhine-Westphalia (LANUV) says.

If the infection is confirmed any further spread of the virus is to
be avoided. In particular, existing blisters should be covered, until
the scab has fallen off. Cowpox virus transmission between humans has
not been proven and is considered unusual. The LANUV recommends not
buying pet rats at present. If animals have been bought recently the
owners should have them examined by a veterinarian, especially when
the animals show lesions on their feet, ears, or tail. Pet rat owners
are advised to wear protective gloves when handling the animals to
protect against infection.

According to findings of the competent health authorities of North
Rhine-Westphalia there is a link between the disease of people from
North Rhine-Westphalia, Bavaria, and northern France. The authorities
report that all pet shops from where the infected animals have been
bought, apparently acquired the rats from the same wholesaler in the
Czech Republic. For more information [in German], see the websites of
LANUV NRW <http://www.lanuv.nrw.de/> and the National Institute for
Health and Work NRW (<http://www.liga.nrw.de/>).

--
