[Sabine Zentis supplied the following additional information:

"According to the RKI (Robert Koch Institut) so far 8 human cases
have been confirmed
<http://www.fli.bund.de/253.html?&no_cache=1&tx_ttnews[tt_news]=688&cHash=713bec3ad6>.
Since the beginning of 2008 an increasing number of humans have been
infected with cowpox virus in the Rhineland region of North
Rhine-Westphalia. Investigations revealed that all these patients had
acquired pet rats prior to becoming ill. Recently various [states]
(Bundeslaender) (Bavaria, North Rhine-Westphalia) reported human
infections with cowpox virus through contact with infected pet rats.
For a long time such infections occurred only sporadically in single
cases, however, at present an increase in numbers of infection
associated with infected pet rats is noted. Cowpox in animals is a
notifiable disease in Germany. Cowpox virus and similar pathogens
such as monkey pox or the smallpox virus of humans (variola virus)
belong to the Genus _Orthopoxvirus_, _family of _Poxviridae_).
Monkeypox and cowpox viruses can pass from animals to humans and are
zoonoses. Cowpox virus can occur in a number of host animals,
although small rodents are regarded a natural virus reservoir. From
this reservoir the virus can spread to numerous other species such as
cattle, cats, and zoo animals (such as, large cats, elephants,
rhinoceros). In certain regions in up to 5 percent of domesticated
cats have antibodies to cowpox virus.

The infection of humans is acquired through even the smallest skin
lesions or mucous membranes during intensive contact with an infected
animal (such as in cattle over milking). Therefore, contact with
infected animals or animals suspected of being infected should be
performed with great care, taking appropriate protective measures.
The severity of infection varies with the animal species involved and
the immune status and ranges from subclinical disease to minor skin
lesions to systemic infection with involvement of numerous organ
systems. After an incubation period of about 3-7 days, in some cases
even up to 14 days, the clinical symptoms seen are the typical
lesions of the skin (rashes, blisters), fatigue, raised temperature,
and conjunctivitis. In severe cases an infection of the lungs
resulting in virus-associated pneumonia can be seen. Secondary
bacterial infections can have an additional negative impact and can
lead to complications.

Very little is known about the course of infection in rats. Rashes
and blisters can be observed (see article in the Deutsches
Tieraerzteblatt 03/2009, at
<http://www.bundestieraerztekammer.de/download/dtb0309_kuhpocken.pdf>
[in German]), but also serious disease leading to the death of the
animal can occur. It should be noted that even animals without
obvious symptoms can excrete the virus and thus can infect other
animals or humans."

[Cowpox virus and monkeypox virus are misnomers, rodents being the
predominant host of both viruses. As indicated by the information
above human cowpox is a rare zoonotic infection, evoking a
self-limiting disease, except in the case of immunocompromised and
eczematous patients, particularly children, where it can become
severe. Cowpox virus, is distributed in Europe, western parts of the
former Soviet Union, and adjacent areas of Northern and Central Asia,
with an increasing number of reports in Europe. Sequencing data have
revealed considerable diversity among isolates of cowpox virus. -
Mod.CP]

[Germany, France, and the Czech Republic can be located on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=51.1,10.4,5>. - CopyEd.MJ]
